04331nam a22005775i 9780822384670DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223846707 a10.1515/97808223846702doi  a(DE-B1597)552135  a(OCoLC)1077292545  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS374.C48bO38 2003 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a813.009/3822211 aOehlschlaeger, Fritz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLove and Good Reasons :bPostliberal Approaches to Christian Ethics and Literature /cFritz Oehlschlaeger. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource (326 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Literary Criticism and Christian Ethics in Service to One Another -- t2. Toward a Christian Ethics of Reading, or, Why We Cannot Be Done with Bartleby -- t3. The ''Best Blessing of Existence'': ''Conscious Worth'' in Emma -- t4. Honor, Faithfulness, and Community in Anthony Trollope's The Warden and He Knew He Was Right -- t5. The ''Very Temple of Authorised Love'': Henry James and The Portrait of a Lady -- t6. A Light That Has Been There from the Beginning: Stephen Crane and the Gospel of John -- tAfterword: Postliberal Christian Scholarship: An Engagement with Rorty and Stout -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInsisting on the vital, productive relationship between ethics and the study of literature, Love and Good Reasons demonstrates ways of reading novels and stories from a Christian perspective. Fritz Oehlschlaeger argues for the study of literature as a training ground for the kinds of thinking on which moral reasoning depends. He challenges methods of doing ethics that attempt to specify universally binding principles or rules and argues for the need to bring literature back into conversation with the most basic questions about how we should live.Love and Good Reasons combines postliberal narrative theology-especially Stanley Hauerwas's Christian ethics and Alasdair MacIntyre's idea of traditional inquiry-with recent scholarship in literature and ethics including the work of Martha Nussbaum, J. Hillis Miller, Wayne Booth, Jeffrey Stout, and Richard Rorty. Oehlschlaeger offers detailed readings of literature by five major authors-Herman Melville, Jane Austen, Anthony Trollope, Henry James, and Stephen Crane. He examines their works in light of biblical scripture and the grand narratives of Israel, Jesus, and the Church. Discussing the role of religion in contemporary higher education, Oehlschlaeger shares his own experiences of teaching literature from a religious perspective at a state university.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAmerican fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aChristian ethics in literature. 0aChristianity and literaturezEnglish-speaking countries. 0aEnglish fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aEthics in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822384670zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822384670423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822384670.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles